<body>

    <h1>File Download Simulation</h1>
    <button id="downloadBtn">Start Download</button>

    <div id="progressContainer">
        <div id="progressBar">0%</div>
    </div>

    <script>
        const downloadBtn = document.getElementById("downloadBtn");
        const progressContainer = document.getElementById("progressContainer");
        const progressBar = document.getElementById("progressBar");

        downloadBtn.addEventListener("click", () => {
            downloadBtn.disabled = true; 
            progressContainer.style.display = "block"; 

            let progress = 0; 

            const interval = setInterval(() => {
                if (progress >= 100) {
                    clearInterval(interval);
                    alert("Download completed"); 
                    downloadBtn.disabled = false; 
                } else {
                    progress += 5; 
                    progressBar.style.width = progress + "%"; 
                    progressBar.textContent = progress + "%"; 
                }
            }, 1000); 
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>


// MongoDB Start From Here 

Model the following Laptop manufacturing information system as a 
graph model, and answer the following queries using Cypher.
Consider an Laptop manufacturing industries which produces different
types of laptops. A customer can buy a laptop, recommend or rate the
product.

1. Identify the labels and relationships, along with their properties, and
   draw a high-level Graph model. 

2. Create nodes and relationships, along with their properties, and
   visualize your actual Graph model.

CREATE
(l1:Laptop {company:'DELL', model:'XPS 15', type:'Ultrabook', specs:'16GB RAM, 512GB SSD'}),
(l2:Laptop {company:'HP', model:'Pavilion', type:'Gaming', specs:'32GB RAM, 1TB SSD'}),
(l3:Laptop {company:'Apple', model:'MacBook Air', type:'Ultrabook', specs:'8GB RAM, 256GB SSD'}),

(c1:Customer {name:'Rahul'}),
(c2:Customer {name:'Sita'}),
(c3:Customer {name:'Amresh'}),

(c1)-[:BOUGHT {date:'2023-01-26'}]->(l1),
(c2)-[:BOUGHT {date:'2023-02-01'}]->(l2),
(c3)-[:BOUGHT {date:'2023-01-26'}]->(l3),

(c1)-[:RECOMMENDED]->(l1),
(c2)-[:RECOMMENDED]->(l2),
(c3)-[:RECOMMENDED]->(l1),

(c1)-[:RATED {rating:5}]->(l1),
(c2)-[:RATED {rating:4}]->(l2),
(c3)-[:RATED {rating:5}]->(l1);

3. Answer the Queries

a. List the characteristics of laptop.  
MATCH (l:Laptop {model:'XPS 15'})
RETURN l.company, l.model, l.type, l.specs;

b. List the names of customers who bought a “DELL” company laptop  
MATCH (c:Customer)-[:BOUGHT]->(l:Laptop {company:'DELL'})
RETURN c.name;

c. List the customers who purchased a device on “26/01/2023”  
MATCH (c:Customer)-[b:BOUGHT]->(l:Laptop)
WHERE b.date = '2023-01-26'
RETURN c.name, l.model;

d. List the most recommended device.  
MATCH (c:Customer)-[:RECOMMENDED]->(l:Laptop)
RETURN l.model, count(c) AS Recommendations
ORDER BY Recommendations DESC
LIMIT 1;
